<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="plotting">
    <title>Plotting, Bisection, and Least Squares</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>Scientific computing often means more than just computing a number&#8212; we also want to <em>see</em> our results. In this chapter we'll learn to plot data straight from a C program using <term>gnuplot</term>, and then put that ability to use in two classic scientific-computing problems: finding the root of an equation with the <term>bisection method</term>, and finding the best-fit line through a set of data points with <term>least squares</term> (linear regression). Here's what we'll cover:
        <ul>
            <li>Plotting with gnuplot</li>
            <li>The bisection method for solving <m>f(x) = 0</m></li>
            <li>Least squares (linear regression)</li>
        </ul>
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="plotting-gnuplot">
        <title>Plotting with gnuplot</title>
        <p><idx>gnuplot</idx><term>gnuplot</term> is a command-line plotting program. Rather than writing data to a file and opening gnuplot separately, we can open a <em>pipe</em> directly to gnuplot from within our C program using <c>popen()</c>, then write gnuplot commands and data to that pipe with <c>fprintf()</c>, exactly as if we were writing to a file:</p>
        <cd>FILE *gfile = popen("gnuplot", "w");
fprintf(gfile, "set terminal png\n");
fprintf(gfile, "set output 'my_plot.png'\n");
fprintf(gfile, "plot '-'\n");        /* '-' means: data follows inline */
/* ... write x,y pairs, one per line ... */
fprintf(gfile, "e\n");               /* 'e' ends the inline data       */
pclose(gfile);</cd>
        <p>Here is a complete, minimal example that plots a single array of data points. Since this code opens a plot window via <c>popen()</c>, which the embedded coding window can't display, it's shown below as read-only: copy it into your own Linux environment and run it there.</p>
        <cmecode startPoint="engs20p_NplotBasic" addOn="&amp;nocheck=true" height="450" forceStatic="yes"></cmecode>
        <p>We can plot multiple curves on the same figure, and add titles and axis labels, by extending the gnuplot commands we send through the pipe. Again, copy this into your own Linux environment to run it and see the plot:</p>
        <cmecode startPoint="engs20p_NplotAdvanced" addOn="&amp;nocheck=true" height="600" forceStatic="yes"></cmecode>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="plotting-bisection">
        <title>The Bisection Method</title>
        <p><idx><h>bisection method</h><h>root-finding</h></idx>We've already met <term>Bisection Search</term> as a way to search a sorted list. The same halving idea can be used to solve equations of the form <m>f(x) = 0</m> for a continuous function <m>f</m>: this is the <term>bisection method</term>.</p>
        <p>Suppose we know that a solution lies somewhere between <m>x=a</m> and <m>x=b</m> (that is, <m>f(a)</m> and <m>f(b)</m> have opposite signs). We compute the midpoint <m>x_1 = (a+b)/2</m>, and check the sign of <m>f(x_1)</m>: if it has the same sign as <m>f(a)</m>, the root must be between <m>x_1</m> and <m>b</m>, so we replace <m>a</m> with <m>x_1</m>. Otherwise, the root is between <m>a</m> and <m>x_1</m>, so we replace <m>b</m> with <m>x_1</m>. Either way, we now have a shorter interval containing the root, and we repeat the process until the interval is <q>short enough</q>.</p>
        <activity xml:id="activity-plotting-bisection">
            <statement>
                <p>We want to write a program that finds the solution of the equation <m>x^3 - 4x - 9 = 0</m> using the bisection method.</p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Write a function <c>float func(float x)</c> that computes <m>f(x) = x^3 - 4x - 9</m>.</li>
                    <li>Populate two arrays with the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates over the interval <m>[a,b] = [2.0, 4.0]</m>, and plot them using gnuplot, as in the previous section.</li>
                    <li>Compute a first estimate <m>x_1 = (a+b)/2</m>. Determine whether the true solution lies between <m>a</m> and <m>x_1</m>, or between <m>x_1</m> and <m>b</m>, by comparing the signs of <m>f(a)</m>, <m>f(x_1)</m>, and <m>f(b)</m>, then replace <m>a</m> or <m>b</m> with <m>x_1</m> to obtain a shorter interval that still contains the solution, and repeat.</li>
                    <li>Come up with a reasonable way to stop once your approximation is <q>good enough</q>, and display the solution both in the terminal and on your graph.</li>
                </ol>
                <p><em>This starting point plots via <c>popen()</c>, so it's shown read-only below &#8212; copy it into your own Linux environment to run it and see the plot.</em></p>
                <cmecode startPoint="engs20p_NbisectionPractice" addOn="&amp;nocheck=true" height="500" forceStatic="yes"></cmecode>
                <p><em>Record your code below.</em></p>
            </statement>
            <response/>
        </activity>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="plotting-leastsquares">
        <title>Least Squares (Linear Regression)</title>
        <p><idx><h>least squares</h></idx><idx><h>linear regression</h></idx>Suppose we have <m>N</m> data points <m>(x_i, y_i)</m> and want to find the straight line <m>y = mx + b</m> that fits them as closely as possible. The <term>least squares</term> method finds the slope <m>m</m> and intercept <m>b</m> that minimize the sum of the squared vertical distances (shown below in green) between the data points and the line, using these formulas:</p>
        <figure>
            <image source="images/LinearRegressionFit.png" width="60%"/>
            <caption>A least-squares line of best fit through four data points, with vertical distances (residuals) shown in green</caption>
        </figure>
        <p><m>\displaystyle m = \frac{N \sum(x_iy_i) - \sum(x_i) \sum(y_i)}{N \sum(x_i^2) - \left(\sum(x_i)\right)^2}</m></p>
        <p><m>\displaystyle b = \frac{\sum(y_i) - m\sum(x_i)}{N}</m></p>
        <p>The example below plots a set of data points along with their least-squares line of best fit. As with the earlier gnuplot examples, this opens a plot window via <c>popen()</c>, so it's shown read-only here &#8212; copy it into your own Linux environment to run it and see the plot.</p>
        <cmecode startPoint="engs20p_NleastSquaresDemo" addOn="&amp;nocheck=true" height="600" forceStatic="yes"></cmecode>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="plotting-summary">
        <title>Summary</title>
        <p>In this chapter, we covered the following topics:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Plotting from C using a pipe to gnuplot</li>
            <li>The bisection method for solving <m>f(x)=0</m></li>
            <li>Least squares (linear regression)</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
</chapter>
